## Section 5 — Learning Reflection

 Today I learned that many problems are not caused by incorrect code but by project configuration. At first i thought there were mistakes in my Queue and URLFrontier implementations because IntelliSense was showing many red errors. However after compiling the project successfully i realized that the code was correct and the errors were only coming from the editor. This taught me that compiler output is more reliable than IntelliSense when debugging C++ projects.

I also understood the importance of templates and project setup. Template implementation files must be included correctly and CMake include paths should be configured properly. Even a small mistake in the project configuration can cause many confusing errors, although the actual implementation is correct.

While implementing the URLValidator i learned that not every Cpp feature works with every compiler i initially used `std::string::starts_with()` but my compiler did not support it because it is a C++20 feature i replaced it with `compare()` which worked with my current compiler and gave the same result.

At the end of the day the URLFrontier module was working properly the Queue was integrated successfully, and the URLValidator was implemented without compilation errors. This has prepared the crawler project for the next modules such as URL Normalizer, Seen Storage, Fetcher, and the Crawler Engine.
